{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624112"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16887"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16887"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.06,0,0.65,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16887"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5143"},{"type":"tags","id":"5144"},{"type":"tags","id":"5323"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman with recently diagnosed ulcerative colitis is prescribed oral mesalazine, a 5-aminosalicylate. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the drug\u0027s primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases intestinal mucus production to protect against inflammation","Blocks tumour necrosis factor alpha receptors","Stimulates epithelial cell regeneration specifically in the intestinal wall","Reduces local inflammatory response mediators, like prostaglandins and leukotrienes","Prevents T cell activation and proliferation at a systemic level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mechanism of action of 5-aminosalicylates is not clearly elucidated, but it is proposed to cause a \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction in local inflammatory response mediators, like prostaglandins and leukotrienes. \u003C/strong\u003EA number of other secondary mechanisms are postulated, such as influence on TNF and T cells. Mesalazine works topically rather than systemically. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExplanation of the incorrect answers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases intestinal mucus production to protect against inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism of action. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks tumour necrosis factor alpha receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of biological agents such as infliximab, not 5-aminosalicylates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates epithelial cell regeneration specifically in the intestinal wall \u003C/strong\u003E is a consequence of reduced inflammation rather than a direct effect of the medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents T cell activation and proliferation at a systemic level\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of immunosuppressive medications such as azathioprine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5-aminosalicylates are particularly effective in treating ulcerative colitis due to their local anti-inflammatory effects on the colonic mucosa. Different formulations allow targeted delivery to specific regions of the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["5-aminosalicylates are thought to work by reducing local inflammatory response mediators like prostaglandins and leukotrienes","5-aminosalicylates are first-line therapy for maintaining remission in ulcerative colitis.","Different formulations of 5-aminosalicylates allow targeted drug delivery to specific regions of the gastrointestinal tract, due to their topical therapeutic effect"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Ye B, van Langenberg DR. Mesalazine preparations for the treatment of ulcerative colitis: Are all created equal?. World J Gastrointest Pharmacol Ther. 2015;6(4):137-144. doi:10.4292/wjgpt.v6.i4.137"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16887"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T11:33:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T11:34:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"creat